```
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <functional>

int main() {
    // File path
    const char* filePath = "path/to/your/file.txt";
    // Open the file and read it line by line
    std::ifstream file(filePath, std::ios::in);
    // Count the number of occurrences of the word
    std::count_if(std::istream_iterator<std::string>(file), std::istream_iterator<std::string>{}, [&](const std::string& line) {
    // Check if the word is present in the line
    return std::string::find(line, "word_to_count") != std::string::npos;
    });
    // Output the count
    std::cout << "Number of occurrences of the word: " << std::endl;
    for (const auto& line : std::count_if(std::istream_iterator<std::string>(file), std::istream_iterator<std::string>{}, [&](const std::string& line) {
    return std::string::find(line, "word_to_count") != std::string::npos;
    })) {
    std::cout << line << " appears " << std::count_if(line, "word_to_count") << " times." << std::endl;
    }
    return 0;

```

In this code, we first specify the path to the text file we want to read. We then open the file using `std::ifstream` and read it line by line using `std::istream_iterator`. We define a lambda function that takes each line as input and checks if it contains the word we want to count. If it does, we increment a count variable. Finally, we output the count for each line.
